{ Blacks position looks cramped. Can you find a way to show that White overextended ? }
1... Nxc5 2. dxc5 Rxd2 3. Nxd2 Bg5
{ This was the idea. White's pieces are uncoordinated and he can't protect d2 easily. }
4. Rd1
{ 25.Qa3  Nc2  -+   25.Ncb1  is the most tenacious defense, but Black still comes out on top.  Bxb1  26.Qxb1  Bxd2  -+  White has some compensation for Black's extra pawn, but it's not enough. }
4... Bc2
{ Game over. White will end up down material. Most tenacious now would be   26.Ncb1  Bxd1  27.Qxd1  Bxd2  28.Nxd2  Qg5  29.Be1  Qxc5+  30.Kh1  Qe3  -+  but White's position is lost. Black has a rook and 2 pawns for 2 pieces and White's coordination is horrible. Black will quickly win additional material. }
